9.0; Current efforts in synthetic vector gene delivery research; StoneSerif
9.0; have primarily focused on the development of systems; StoneSerif
9.0; designed to address particular individual barriers to effi-; StoneSerif
9.0; cient gene delivery in an isolated rather than an integrated; StoneSerif
9.0; fashion. At the cellular level, these barriers include, but are; StoneSerif
9.0; not limited to, inefficient vector/cell binding and inter-; StoneSerif
9.0; nalization, subcellular trafficking for degradation by lyso-; StoneSerif
9.0; somes related to poor endosomal escape characteristics,; StoneSerif
9.0; degradation by cytoplasmic nucleases, nuclear import, vec-; StoneSerif
9.0; tor unpackaging, and gene expression (Fig. 1). However,; StoneSerif
9.0; as vectors are developed that overcome a potentially ; StoneSerif
9.0; limiting step, other barriers can in turn become predom-; StoneSerif
9.0; inant. Therefore, a multi-parameter systems analysis based; StoneSerif
9.0; on quantitative methodologies should be useful for design-; StoneSerif
9.0; ing and fully characterizing synthetic vectors. Such quan-; StoneSerif
9.0; titative techniques serve to facilitate vector evolution; StoneSerif
9.0; through identification of rate-limiting barriers as they; StoneSerif
9.0; relate to cellular and vector parameters. Mechanistic level; StoneSerif
9.0; multiple vector comparisons can be performed, providing; StoneSerif
9.0; insight into molecular attributes yielding efficient gene; StoneSerif
9.0; delivery. Using such information, rational design of novel; StoneSerif
9.0; vectors becomes possible. The questions evolve from ask-; StoneSerif
9.0; ing if one vector works better than another, where relative; StoneSerif
9.0; light units or GFP expression is considered the metric of; StoneSerif
9.0; gene delivery success, to asking why, where, and how one; StoneSerif
9.0; vector works better than another.; StoneSerif
9.0; Computational modeling offers a powerful tool for; StoneSerif
9.0; such systems-based investigation. Imperative for the; StoneSerif
9.0; development and implementation of models is founding; StoneSerif
9.0; their basis in quantitative experimental techniques. Real-; StoneSerif
9.0; time PCR allows for the direct measure of plasmid levels; StoneSerif
9.0; from cells and subcellular compartments, and we have; StoneSerif
9.0; used it here in combination with literature data to help; StoneSerif
9.0; validate our model. Transfection of C3A cells with a GFP; StoneSerif
9.0; plasmid by means of Lipofectamine resulted in a rapid; StoneSerif
9.0; increase in total cellular plasmids, with delayed nuclear; StoneSerif
9.0; association (Fig. 2). Cellular uptake reached a maximum; StoneSerif
9.0; at 120 minutes, after which saturation of uptake occurred; StoneSerif
9.0; and plasmids were lost to cytoplasmic degradation.; StoneSerif
